<p style=3D"text-align:justify"><strong>Objective</strong>: This course pro=
vides a strong foundation to aid comprehension in contemporary
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">trends in advanced engineering materials. A=
t the end of this course, the student will
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">understand basic principles in the discipli=
ne and will be able relate them to materials engineering practice.
</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Contents</strong>:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">Material selection principles, Advances in =
ferrous and non-ferrous alloys, Intermetallics,
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">Ceramics, Composites, &nbsp;Energy material=
s (fuel cells, batteries, energy storage systems, etc.),
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">Biomaterials, Magnetic materials, Supercond=
uctors, Nanomaterials--&nbsp;synthesis and processing,
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">light-emitting materials, low-dimensional m=
aterials (principles, processing and applications).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Text Books</strong>:</p>
